Design Rationale

Single decision per policy: Each policy should communicate its intent at a glance. Multi-rule policies created confusion about what a policy "does." The team agreed that simplicity and readability outweigh the flexibility of bundling related rules.

unless naming: Reads naturally as English — "Allow X unless Y." Consistent with Cedar (AWS Verified Permissions) which uses unless as a condition clause on both permit and forbid.

unless on both ALLOW and DENY: Industry standard (Cedar, Cerbos, OPA, AWS IAM) supports conditions on both decision types for language orthogonality. Documentation will advocate ALLOW + unless as the primary pattern.

Priority-based evaluation: Enables explicit override semantics (e.g., executive exemptions) and configurable defaults via catch-all policies, replacing the hardcoded "no match = ALLOW" behavior.

Custom taxonomies as match dimensions: Eliminates the data_use_taxonomies/data_category_taxonomies distinction. A custom taxonomy key like commercial_classification is used directly in the match block, same syntax as built-in dimensions.

Security model change: The original PRD stated "DENY rules are absolute — if ANY DENY rule matches, the decision is DENY regardless of ALLOW rules." This revision replaces that guarantee with priority-based evaluation where a high-priority ALLOW can override a lower-priority DENY. This is an intentional change to support exemption policies, but it means a misconfigured high-priority ALLOW could inadvertently override safety-critical DENY policies. Administrators should treat high-priority ALLOW policies with the same scrutiny as DENY policy deletions. Consider restricting priority assignment above a threshold (e.g., priority > 400) to admin-only roles.

