The policy list view should support grouping/filtering by control. A dedicated "Controls" view showing all controls with their associated policies is recommended.

5.4 Migration from Current Schema

Existing multi-rule policies must be split into individual policies during migration. Each rule becomes its own policy, inheriting the parent policy's metadata.

Structural transformation:

Each rule in a multi-rule policy becomes a separate policy

The original policy's fides_key goes to the first rule; subsequent rules get suffixed keys (e.g., original_key_rule_2)

All split policies inherit the parent's name, description, and enabled state

All split policies default to priority: 0 (admin should assign appropriate priorities post-migration)

Semantic transformation (constraints → unless):

The constraints block used positive-gate logic (conditions that must pass for ALLOW). The unless block uses inverted logic (conditions that, when met, block the decision). Consent requirement values must be mapped:

PRD constraint (requirement)

Spec unless (requirement)

Explanation

opt_in (must have opted in)

not_opt_in (block if NOT opted in)

Same intent, inverted framing

not_opt_out (must not have opted out)

opt_out (block if opted out)

Same intent, inverted framing

Geo location transformation: operator: not_in (constraint: pass if NOT in these locations) becomes operator: in (unless: trigger if IN these locations), and vice versa.

Existing DENY rules: DENY rules in the current schema cannot have constraints, so they require no constraint-related transformation — only the structural split.

Taxonomy match syntax: The changes table notes that data_use_taxonomies/data_category_taxonomies syntax changed to direct taxonomy keys. However, taxonomy-based matching is a v2-only feature — no v1 policies use this syntax, so no migration is needed for match block taxonomy references.

Coexistence: v1 and v2 policy schemas will not coexist. Migration is a one-way upgrade applied during the v2 release.

